<body> 
 <pb n="1" id="Tw9012271">  
<div1 type="letter"> 
<opener> 
<seg><figure entity="T901227a"> 
<figDesc>Papers of Mark Twain, AL 1890 Dec 27, 
Mark Twain, Hartford, CT, to Fred J. Hall;  
image of page one of the manuscript. 
</figDesc> 
</figure> 
</seg> 
<dateline><name type="place">Hartford</name>,  
<date n="1890-12-27"><abbr expan="December">Dec.</abbr> 27/90. 
</date></dateline>  
<salute>Dear Mr. Hall:</salute>  
</opener> 
<p>I don't believe Whitford. <lb> 
Webster was too big a coward <lb> 
to bring a suit when advised <lb> 
against it.  The real mistake <lb> 
was in trusting law business <lb> 
to an ignorant, blethering <lb> 
gas-pipe like Whitford. <lb> 
I am not saying this in <lb> 
hatred, for I do not dislike <lb> 
Whitford.  He is simply a <lb> 
damned fool &mdash; in Court &mdash; <lb> 
&amp; will infallibly lose every <lb> 
suit you put into his hands. <lb> 
If you are going to have <lb> 
 
 
   <pb n="2" id="Tw9012272">  
 
<figure entity="T901227b"> 
<figDesc>Papers of Mark Twain, AL 1890 Dec 27, 
Mark Twain, Hartford, CT, to Fred J. Hall;  
image of page two of the manuscript. 
</figDesc> 
</figure> 
 
any <del>[illeg.]</del><add place="overwritten">lawsuits</add> with Gill, <lb> 
I beg that you will either <lb> 
compromise or have <lb> 
some other law conduct <lb> 
the thing.</p> 
  
<p>I am mighty sorry <lb> 
for you, but this result <lb> 
was to be expected.  If I <lb> 
were you I would ask <orig reg="Whitford">Whit- <lb> 
ford</orig> to present a modified <lb> 
bill &mdash; or better still, present <lb> 
it to the parties he won the <lb> 
case for.</p>  
 
<p>Merry <abbr expan="Christmas">Xmas</abbr> to you! &mdash; <lb> 
&amp; I wish to <del>g</del><add place="overwritten" n="God">G</add>od I could have <lb> 
one myself before I die.</p>  
 
<closer> 
<salute><abbr expan="Yours">Ys</abbr> Ever </salute>  
<signed>SLC</signed>  
 
</closer> 
</div1> 
   
